</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,324,597,623]" box="[189,324,597,623]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,597,623]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,597,623]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1399,645,709]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
From the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[381,443,645,671]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">tūbĕr</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘protuberance’, and ‘ 
<emphasis box="[822,892,645,671]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">caulis</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘stem’, to illustrate the presence of putative nematothecae on stems.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,303,749,775]" box="[189,303,749,775]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,749,775]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,749,775]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1398,797,1008]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Galea &amp; Schuchert, 2019" authorityName="Galea &amp; Schuchert" authorityYear="2019" box="[312,471,797,823]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Symplectoscyphidae" genus="Tuberocaulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[312,471,797,823]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Tuberocaulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[475,579,798,824]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is monotypic so far and comprises 
<taxonomicName authority="(Vervoort, 1993)" authorityName="Galea &amp; Schuchert" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Vervoort" baseAuthorityYear="1993" class="Hydrozoa" family="Symplectoscyphidae" genus="Tuberocaulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="scorpioides" status="gen. et comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[976,1274,797,823]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Tuberocaulus scorpioides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Vervoort" firstAuthor="Vervoort" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="89 - 298" refId="ref39987" refString="Vervoort W. 1993. Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Hydroida: Hydroids from the western Pacific (Philippines, Indonesia and New Caledonia) I. Sertulariidae (Part 1). In: Crosnier A. (ed.) Resultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM, Vol. 11. Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle 158: 89 - 298." type="journal article" year="1993">Vervoort, 1993</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[265,482,834,861]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" rank="species">gen. et comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
This species was originally placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[932,1262,834,860]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Sertulariidae" genus="Thyroscyphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1094,834,860]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Thyroscyphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Allman" box="[1100,1262,834,860]" firstAuthor="Allman" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref35871" refString="Allman G. J. 1877. Report on the Hydroida collected during the exploration of the Gulf Stream by L. F. de Pourtales, Assistant United States Coast Survey. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College 5 (2): 1 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10420" type="journal article" year="1877">Allman, 1877</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
on account of the attachment of the hydranth to the inner hydrothecal wall (whose surface is lined by “a sheath of tissue” = mantle) “by means of a circular fold”. However, unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[964,1126,908,934]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Sertulariidae" genus="Thyroscyphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[964,1126,908,934]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Thyroscyphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the hydrotheca of this species is given off from the internode, and it is not borne on a distinct apophysis; additionally, it has a well-defined (though short) adnate adaxial wall, as well as a base (see description above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1399,1048,1149]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
The fascicled condition of the stem and its peculiar appearance, the presence of what appears to be stem nematothecae, as well as the unilateral arrangement of cladia and their hydrothecae, are not features shared by the genus of 
<bibRefCitation author="Allman" box="[459,636,1122,1148]" firstAuthor="Allman" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref35871" refString="Allman G. J. 1877. Report on the Hydroida collected during the exploration of the Gulf Stream by L. F. de Pourtales, Assistant United States Coast Survey. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College 5 (2): 1 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10420" type="journal article" year="1877">Allman (1877)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1399,1189,1363]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
The systematic position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Galea &amp; Schuchert" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Vervoort" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[519,686,1189,1215]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Symplectoscyphidae" genus="Tuberocaulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="scorpioides">
<emphasis box="[519,686,1189,1215]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">T. scorpioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could not be ascertained on morphological grounds alone. Indeed, its long, tubular, tricuspidate hydrothecae superficially recall those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lamouroux, 1816)" authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityYear="1816" baseAuthorityName="Lamouroux" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Hydrozoa" family="Thyroscyphidae" genus="Parascyphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[1146,1399,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Parascyphus simplex</emphasis>
(Lamouroux, 1816)
</taxonomicName>
, but in that species, the thecae are borne on distinct stem apophyses, their ‘bases’ are represented by an internal annular thickening of the perisarc, and the marginal cusps adopt a different position (one adaxial and two latero-abaxial cusps, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Galea" box="[837,1042,1337,1363]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Galea" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 50" refId="ref37340" refString="Galea H. R., Schories D., Forsterra G. &amp; Haussermann V. 2014. New species and new records of hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) from Chile. Zootaxa 3852 (1): 1 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3852.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Galea 
<emphasis box="[912,964,1337,1363]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1399,1404,1541]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
Being fused to the corresponding internodes, the hydrothecae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Galea &amp; Schuchert" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Vervoort" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[995,1164,1404,1430]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Symplectoscyphidae" genus="Tuberocaulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="scorpioides">
<emphasis box="[995,1164,1404,1430]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">T. scorpioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reminiscent of those met with in members of the Sertulariida 
<bibRefCitation author="Maronna" box="[733,979,1440,1467]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Maronna" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="18075" refId="ref38063" refString="Maronna M. M., Miranda T. P., Pena Cantero A. L., Barbeitos M. S. &amp; Marques A. C. 2016. Towards a phylogenetic classification of Leptothecata (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa). Nature, Scientific Reports 6: 18075. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / srep 18075" type="journal article" year="2016">
Maronna 
<emphasis box="[846,898,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al</emphasis>
., 2016
</bibRefCitation>
(with only 
<taxonomicName authority="Vervoort, 1993" authorityName="Vervoort" authorityYear="1993" box="[1115,1399,1441,1467]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Sertulariidae" genus="Gonaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1115,1216,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Gonaxia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Vervoort" box="[1222,1399,1441,1467]" firstAuthor="Vervoort" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="89 - 298" refId="ref39987" refString="Vervoort W. 1993. Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Hydroida: Hydroids from the western Pacific (Philippines, Indonesia and New Caledonia) I. Sertulariidae (Part 1). In: Crosnier A. (ed.) Resultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM, Vol. 11. Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle 158: 89 - 298." type="journal article" year="1993">Vervoort, 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
showing the same position of the marginal cusps), although nematothecae have never been reported in any genus belonging to it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="53.[189,1399,1581,1681]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
The relationship of 
<taxonomicName authority="Galea &amp; Schuchert, 2019" authorityName="Galea &amp; Schuchert" authorityYear="2019" box="[414,589,1581,1607]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Thyroscyphidae" genus="Tuberoscyphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[414,589,1581,1607]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Tuberoscyphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[594,699,1582,1608]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
to the other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cornelius" authorityYear="1992" box="[840,992,1581,1607]" class="Hydrozoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="order">Leptothecata</taxonomicName>
families remains to be investigated by molecular phylogenies. In the absence of such studies for the time being, the genus is left provisionally in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stechow" authorityYear="1920" box="[262,455,1655,1681]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Thyroscyphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Thyroscyphidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
